%I A283056 #31 Mar 25 2026 23:51:37
%S A283056 0,7,9,11,11,13,13,15,15,15,17,17,17,19,19
%N A283056 Size of the smallest polyomino that admits a hole of size n.
%C A283056 The task here is to surround a hole of size n with the least number of squares. The hole is another polyomino, so we can obtain a lower bound using A027709: minimal perimeter of polyomino with n square cells. We need an extra 3 (or more) diagonal cells to surround any hole. Hence a(n) >= A027709(n) + 3 = 2*ceiling(2*sqrt(n)) + 3.
%C A283056 For rectangular holes we can obtain an upper bound using A262767: minimum perimeter of a rectangle with area n and integer sides. Hence a(n) <= A262767(n) + 3.
%C A283056 Perhaps a(n) is actually equal to A027709(n)+3?
%C A283056 From _Peter Exley_, Mar 25 2026: (Start)
%C A283056 a(7)-a(14) proved by exhaustive enumeration of all free n-ominoes (candidate hole shapes). For each shape H, the minimum connected shell is computed as corona(H) plus Steiner bridge cells. The minimum over all shapes gives a(n). Cross-validated against an independent SAT solver (PySAT/CaDiCaL) for n <= 8.
%C A283056 For all proved values n = 0..14, the optimal hole is a minimum-perimeter polyomino with corona in exactly 4 connected components, requiring exactly 3 bridge cells. This gives a(n) = A027709(n) + 3 for n = 0..14.
%C A283056 Upper bounds: a(15) <= 19, a(16) <= 19, a(17) <= 21, a(18) <= 21, a(19) <= 21, a(20) <= 21.
%C A283056 Conjecture (Dmitry Kamenetsky, 2017): a(n) = A027709(n) + 3 for n >= 1. All proved values a(0)-a(14) and upper bounds a(15)-a(20) are consistent with this conjecture. (End)
%H A283056 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A283056">Solver code, data, and figures</a>, GitHub.
%e A283056 For n=1, we have a single square hole, so a(1)=7.
%e A283056 For n=2, we have a domino hole, so a(2)=9.
%e A283056 For n=3, we can use either an L or V tromino hole, so a(3)=11.
%e A283056 For n=4, we use the square tetromino hole, so a(4)=11.
%e A283056 For n=5, we use the P pentomino hole, so a(5)=13.
%e A283056 For n=6, we use the 2 X 3 rectangle hole, so a(6)=13.
%e A283056 From _Peter Exley_, Mar 25 2026: (Start)
%e A283056 For n = 9, the smallest container has a(9) = 15 cells on a 5 X 5 grid:
